   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The table compares each cluster with the overall customer average using a lift ratio. Values above 1 indicate that the cluster is above the average for that variable, while values below 1 indicate that it is below the average.\n",
    "\n",
    "The lift table shows clear differences between the customer clusters. Big families are the most distinct in terms of household size, with dependants at 3.57 times the overall average. They also have much higher total spending (1.53) and buy a wider variety of products (2.00), which supports the idea that larger households have broader and higher consumption needs. However, they buy fewer products on promotion (0.65), suggesting that this group is less discount-driven.\n",
    "\n",
    "Bargain hunters are clearly the most promotion-oriented cluster, with a promotion value of 1.70, meaning they buy products on promotion much more often than the average customer. However, their total spending is lower (0.60) and their product variety is also below average (0.58), which suggests a more selective and price-sensitive shopping behaviour.\n",
    "\n",
    "The Karens cluster also shows a strong connection with promotions (1.42) and has more dependants than average (1.31**), but lower store diversity (0.70) and lower product variety (0.50). This may indicate a more focused shopping pattern, with customers buying fewer types of products but being more attentive to promotions.\n",
    "\n",
    "Gamers and Tech enthusiasts have very low numbers of dependants, with values of 0.36 and 0.27, respectively. They also visit fewer stores than average, especially Tech enthusiasts (0.46) and Gamers (0.53). However, both clusters shop later than average, with typical hour values of 1.33 for Gamers and 1.37 for Tech enthusiasts, suggesting a different shopping routine compared to the other groups.\n",
    "\n",
    "The Loyal core spenders cluster appears more stable and valuable, with above-average customer tenure (1.12), store visits (1.09) and product variety (1.42). Their promotion value is exactly around the average (1.00), which suggests that they are not especially discount-driven but still represent a consistent customer segment.\n",
    "\n",
    "Finally, Vegans stand out due to their higher education level (1.48) and very low promotion usage (0.41). This suggests that this group is less motivated by discounts and may be more driven by specific product preferences. Overall, the table confirms that the cluster names are meaningful, since each group presents different behaviours in terms of household size, spending, promotion sensitivity, shopping habits and product variety."
   ]
  },
